</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="5F83DC7EE7EB1C9F890EB1749D2773AB" pageId="0" pageNumber="107" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="53EE071385E77E5D2068A50D835E54A1" pageId="0" pageNumber="107">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D1BAF552369F68445F5803C8C23395BA" pageId="0" pageNumber="107">
Unlike 
<taxonomicName id="4C09272F561035047617CC9923B5C6FD" class="Gastropoda" family="Ampullariidae" genus="Pila" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pila" order="Architaenioglossa" pageId="0" pageNumber="107" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="31B37FDA4812040E8798F16008AE0F35" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="107">Pila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species, 
<taxonomicName id="D3165C1F431E45953BCFECE4B6A7BBD7" authorityName="Perry" authorityYear="1810" class="Gastropoda" family="Ampullariidae" genus="Pomacea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pomacea maculata" order="Architaenioglossa" pageId="0" pageNumber="107" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="maculata">
<emphasis id="510F12EB4FF20DFE41644A55C04EF243" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="107">Pomacea maculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is not native to Southeast Asia. 
<taxonomicName id="43896FB22B4D2BC812407690BC9482AD" authorityName="Perry" authorityYear="1810" class="Gastropoda" family="Ampullariidae" genus="Pomacea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pomacea maculata" order="Architaenioglossa" pageId="0" pageNumber="107" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="maculata">
<emphasis id="34849D8DF6DB03E46ED91FAD22227D3B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="107">Pomacea maculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(as 
<taxonomicName id="A330B4A44EF95C8F067AB2717ABD4231" baseAuthorityName="d'Orbigny" baseAuthorityYear="1835" class="Gastropoda" family="Ampullariidae" genus="Pomacea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pomacea insularum" order="Architaenioglossa" pageId="0" pageNumber="107" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="insularum">
<emphasis id="8CFD2626D93BF4356B118EE12A2DA33E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="107">Pomacea insularum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken id="296E434DEC0B95BD2A5C32D578F92F2E" originalValue="d’Orbigny">d'Orbigny</normalizedToken>
, 1835 in Hayes 2008), and another species, 
<taxonomicName id="A61BDA93749DCBE02461CF4A0207BBC0" baseAuthorityName="Lamarck" baseAuthorityYear="1822" class="Gastropoda" family="Ampullariidae" genus="Pomacea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pomacea canaliculata" order="Architaenioglossa" pageId="0" pageNumber="107" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="canaliculata">
<emphasis id="F7D1B50342D3C3A5D52085871BE852E5" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="107">Pomacea canaliculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Lamarck, 1822), have both been introduced to Asia from South America (
<bibRefCitation id="419495D5C62352282D371DDB5839B8B9" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1096-3642.2012.00867.x" author="Hayes, KA" journalOrPublisher="Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society" pageId="0" pageNumber="107" pagination="723 - 753" refId="B30" refString="Hayes, KA, Cowie, RH, Thiengo, SC, Strong, EE, 2012. Comparing apples with apples: clarifying the identities of two highly invasive Neotropical Ampullariidae (Caenogastropoda). Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society 166: 723 - 753, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1096-3642.2012.00867.x" title="Comparing apples with apples: clarifying the identities of two highly invasive Neotropical Ampullariidae (Caenogastropoda)." url="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1096-3642.2012.00867.x" volume="166" year="2012">Hayes et al. 2012</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="0655D0E604EE04CFD0E1B2F185AF1BC9" author="Joshi, RC" journalOrPublisher="Philippine Rice Research Institute, Nueva Ecija" pageId="0" pageNumber="107" refId="B35" refString="Joshi, RC, Cowie, RH, Sebastian, LS, 2017. Biology and Management of Invasive Apple Snails. Philippine Rice Research Institute, Nueva Ecija" title="Biology and Management of Invasive Apple Snails." year="2017">Joshi et al. 2017</bibRefCitation>
). Molecular methods are the most accurate way to distinguish between them (Rama Rao et al. 2018), and DNA barcodes of two individuals from the Tonle Sap basin were a match to 
<taxonomicName id="3DF36A64F6B7F8347C37274555C45A93" authorityName="Perry" authorityYear="1810" class="Gastropoda" family="Ampullariidae" genus="Pomacea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pomacea maculata" order="Architaenioglossa" pageId="0" pageNumber="107" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="maculata">
<emphasis id="078FB3F2B17113CC34FD9B36AD93093F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="107">Pomacea maculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(GenBank Accession No. MT372328, MT372329). Because of the morphological similarity between the two species, some records of 
<taxonomicName id="06F712759D18EA0465BB7A19B4DAE3A0" baseAuthorityName="Lamarck" baseAuthorityYear="1822" class="Gastropoda" family="Ampullariidae" genus="Pomacea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pomacea canaliculata" order="Architaenioglossa" pageId="0" pageNumber="107" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="canaliculata">
<emphasis id="A073CAEEDB5FCEA4320DFFFFA9A024C9" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="107">Pomacea canaliculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in Southeast Asia, including in Cambodia, may instead have been of 
<taxonomicName id="BD2DE10AC1F99CFBDB97A92B26DE4802" authorityName="Perry" authorityYear="1810" class="Gastropoda" family="Ampullariidae" genus="Pomacea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pomacea maculata" order="Architaenioglossa" pageId="0" pageNumber="107" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="maculata">
<emphasis id="C740A729B10E6582658A97ACDE5A16F4" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="107">Pomacea maculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see 
<bibRefCitation id="088AA9AAAE772AAC09EBC2740728D890" author="Cowie, RH" editor="Francis, RA" journalOrPublisher="Earthscan, Oxon" pageId="0" pageNumber="107" pagination="207 - 221" refId="B15" refString="Cowie, RH, Hayes, KA, 2012. Apple snails. In: Francis, RA, Ed., A Handbook of Global Freshwater Invasive Species. Earthscan, Oxon: 207 - 221" title="Apple snails." volumeTitle="A Handbook of Global Freshwater Invasive Species." year="2012">Cowie and Hayes 2012</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="EF21815145E89E39D892E26AAACA5104" class="Gastropoda" family="Ampullariidae" genus="Pomacea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pomacea" order="Architaenioglossa" pageId="0" pageNumber="107" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="70409687879B7EFB102BD88F000CE4EA" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="107">Pomacea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species were first recorded in Cambodia only in the mid-1990s (compared to early 1980s in neighbouring Thailand), and even then, had only been collected from three localities (
<bibRefCitation id="E18DC0462E02A1BA8608E42A3AE8867B" author="Cowie, RH" journalOrPublisher="Hydrology and Earth System Sciences" pageId="0" pageNumber="107" refId="B13" refString="Cowie, RH, 1995. Report on a Visit to Cambodia to Advise on Apple Snails as Potential Rice Pests. Unpublished report, 10 pp." title="Report on a Visit to Cambodia to Advise on Apple Snails as Potential Rice Pests. Unpublished report, 10 pp." year="1995">Cowie 1995</bibRefCitation>
). From then onwards, 
<taxonomicName id="AEE1983C4C9CF910A2469A57CF987B8E" class="Gastropoda" family="Ampullariidae" genus="Pomacea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pomacea" order="Architaenioglossa" pageId="0" pageNumber="107" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="D7E1E0A7ABD01C3624B64087D09FABD9" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="107">Pomacea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp. may have spread because these snails were mistaken for native ampullariids and were translocated to paddy fields in attempts to breed them for food - unfortunately, 
<taxonomicName id="9D50A6371594C5BE41823366F205605A" class="Gastropoda" family="Ampullariidae" genus="Pomacea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pomacea" order="Architaenioglossa" pageId="0" pageNumber="107" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="CA7A431E84E46DEC91FD57E233EAA317" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="107">Pomacea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp. became pests that destroyed the crops instead (
<bibRefCitation id="C8FD4A623F908E274E6209ADA58A8F63" author="Khay, S" journalOrPublisher="Fish for the People" pageId="0" pageNumber="107" pagination="34 - 37" refId="B38" refString="Khay, S, Joshi, RC, Sastroutomo, SS, 2018. Invasive apple snails: integrated management in lowland ricefields of Cambodia and probing their utilization in aquaculture. Fish for the People 16 (3): 34 - 37" title="Invasive apple snails: integrated management in lowland ricefields of Cambodia and probing their utilization in aquaculture." volume="16" year="2018">Khay et al. 2018</bibRefCitation>
). At present, 
<taxonomicName id="31E55BDE37A5E91D0B0EBC72392196B0" authorityName="Perry" authorityYear="1810" class="Gastropoda" family="Ampullariidae" genus="Pomacea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pomacea maculata" order="Architaenioglossa" pageId="0" pageNumber="107" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="maculata">
<emphasis id="2DBFBB225476D1791919DC921CE8F8BC" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="107">Pomacea maculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appears to be widespread in the Tonle Sap basin.
</paragraph>
